{{also|Yar|þar|y ar|'yar|yâr|yar-|yär-|ƴar}}
==English==
===Pronunciation===
* {{a|GA}} {{IPA|en|/jɑɹ/}}
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/jɑː/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-yar.wav|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɑː(ɹ)|s=1}}
===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|[[ȝaren]], [[ȝurren]], [[ȝeorren]]}}, from {{inh|en|ang|[[ġeorran]], [[ġirran]], [[gyrran]]||to sound, chatter, grunt, creak, grate}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*gerraną||to creak}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*gʰer-||to make a noise, rattle, gurgle, grumble}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|yarr}}, {{m|sco|yirr||to snarl, growl, quarrel, cause trouble}}, {{cog|gmh|girren||to roar, cry, rattle, chatter}}.
====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|yarr}}
====Verb====
{{en-verb}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[snarl]]; to [[gnar]].
# {{lb|en|intransitive|chiefly|Scotland}} To [[growl]], especially like a dog; [[quarrel]]; to be [[captious]] or [[troublesome]].
===Etymology 2===
Origin uncertain.
====Adjective====
{{en-adj}}
# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialectal}} [[sour|Sour]]; [[brackish]].
=====Derived terms=====
* {{l|en|yarrish}}
===Etymology 3===
From {{inh|en|enm|yar}}, {{m|enm|ȝar}}, variants of {{m|enm|yare}}, {{m|enm|ȝare}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ġearu||ready}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*garu}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*garwaz}}.
====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|yare}}
====Adjective====
{{en-adj|er}}
# {{lb|en|nautical|of a vessel, especially [[sailboat]]}} Quick and agile; easy to [[hand]], [[reef]] and [[steer]].
#*'''1390'''   J. Gower, ''[[w:Confessio Amantis|Confessio Amantis]]'' II. 237
#*:The wynd was good, the Schip was yare.
#* '''1939''', [[w:The Philadelphia Story|''The Philadelphia Story'']] written by {{w|Philip Barry}}
#*: My, she was '''yar'''...It means, uh...easy to handle, quick to the helm, fast, right. Everything a boat should be, until she develops dry rot.
#* '''1958''', ''Bulletin of the John Rylands Library''
#*: ...to make a ship best weighed, or '''yarest''' in her going.
#* '''1993''' Captain McAllister, ''[[w:Simpsons|The Simpsons]]'' ep. [[w:Boy-Scoutz_N_the_Hood|1F06]]
#*: Arr, here be a fine vessel: the '''yarest''' river-going boat there be.
=====Synonyms=====
* {{l|en|yare}}
